body:
IntelliJ seems to indicate that we are accessing UI components from a background thread.

Steps to reproduce: I was following installation instructions:

> Flutter plugin installation
> 
> During alpha development, the Flutter plugin is hosted in its own plugin repository. Before it can be installed, the repository needs to be added to the IDE.
> 
> Open plugin preferences (Preferences>Plugins on macOS, File>Settings>Plugins on Linux)
> Select "Browse repositories…"
> In the Browse Repositories dialog, click "Manage repositories…"
> In the resulting Custom Plugin Repositories pop-up, click the + button and paste https://flutter.github.io/flutter-intellij/alpha/updatePlugins.xml into the Repository URL: field and click OK
> In the Browse Repositories dialog, select flutter-intellij from the list of plugins (be sure it is not being filtered out of your results view by specifying Category: All or limiting it to the Flutter repository in the pull-down by the search box) and click the green Install button
> Once downloaded, click the Restart IntelliJ IDEA button
> Flutter plugin configuration
> 
> Open preferences (Preferences on macOS, File>Settings on Linux)
> Select Languages & Frameworks>Flutter
> Set the path to the root of your flutter repo
> Click OK

Exception occurred after the final OK click. Happens again after restart of IntelliJ and repetition of the last four steps above.

Curious if the Dart analysis server exceptions ring any bells for @scheglov or @jwren?
We found a resolution: Mikkel was using IJ 2016.1. After upgrading to 2016.2 the problem went away.

The best kind of resolution. 👍 

Thanks!
Should we be testing for the IJ versioning and prompt the user to upgrade? I would think many external developers might still be on 2016.1!?

Just add `<idea-version since-build="xxx" until-build="xxx"/>` to `plugin.xml` or make sure Gradle build adds it if the plugin is built with gradle.
For example to target the latest 2016.2.5 use:

```
<idea-version since-build="162.2228" until-build="162.*"/>
```

Or if any 2016.2.x is ok then just:

```
<idea-version since-build="162.1" until-build="162.*"/>
```

In flutter-plugin branch that targets 2016.3 use this or more specific `since`:

```
<idea-version since-build="163.1" until-build="163.*"/>
```

I wouldn't recommend to create plugin builds that target multiple major IDE versions like `<idea-version since-build="162.1" until-build="163.*"/>`.
You wan't be able to install incompatible plugin from the plugin repository.
That's what I would expect.  I'm just wondering if it tells you why.  More specifically, does it tell you that you need to upgrade your IDE version?
I think IDE shows only latest compatible plugins. I guess you won't see the plugin if there's no plugin build for your version. Try to make sure.

Are we likely to often only support the very latest release of IJ, or is it a special case this first time around? If we will generally support a few releases back, then I am fine with the simple option 1.

My preference would be to support as wide a swath of compatible IDEs as possible but we'll see how that goes in practice.  In any event, I think we can safely opt for option 1 and then upgrade if needed.  Thanks!

Not sure I understand the problem that you try to solve. There are no options actually. You publish only working and tested plugin builds with appropriate `since-build` in each. You do not publish incompatible plugins for older IDE versions just to make people think that you support it.

P.S. Issue title says 'exception' but no exception pasted, only a thread dump. Nevermind.
